[ASSISTANT] If you want to restrict the user from entering more than 10 characters in an `EditText` using a `TextWatcher`, you can modify the `afterTextChanged` method as follows:

```kotlin
editText.addTextChangedListener(object : TextWatcher {
    override fun beforeTextChanged(s: CharSequence?, start: Int, count: Int, after: Int) {
        // Not used in this example
    }

    override fun onTextChanged(s: CharSequence?, start: Int, before: Int, count: Int) {
        // Not used in this example
    }

    override fun afterTextChanged(s: Editable?) {
        if (s?.length ?: 0 > 10) {
            editText.setText(s?.subSequence(0, 10)) // Truncate the text to 10 characters
            editText.setSelection(10) // Set the cursor position to the end
        }
    }
})
```

In the `afterTextChanged` method, we check if the length of the entered text (`s`) exceeds 10 characters. If it does, we truncate the text to the first 10 characters using `subSequence(0, 10)` and set the new text using `setText`. Additionally, we set the cursor position to the end of the text using `setSelection(10)`.

This way, the user will not be able to enter more than 10 characters in the `EditText`, and any additional characters entered will be automatically removed.

