[ASSISTANT] Sure! Here's an example of a Kotlin function that generates random names:

```kotlin
fun generateRandomName(): String {
    val vowels = listOf("a", "e", "i", "o", "u")
    val consonants = listOf(
        "b", "c", "d", "f", "g", "h", "j", "k", "l", "m", 
        "n", "p", "q", "r", "s", "t", "v", "w", "x", "y", "z"
    )
    val random = java.util.Random()

    val nameLength = random.nextInt(4) + 4 // Random length between 4 and 7 characters
    var name = ""

    for (i in 0 until nameLength) {
        if (i % 2 == 0) {
            name += consonants[random.nextInt(consonants.size)]
        } else {
            name += vowels[random.nextInt(vowels.size)]
        }
    }

    return name.capitalize()
}
```

This function generates random names by alternating between consonants and vowels. The length of the name is randomly determined to be between 4 and 7 characters. Each character is selected randomly from the `vowels` and `consonants` lists. Finally, the generated name is capitalized before being returned.

You can call this function wherever you need a random name, like this:

```kotlin
val randomName = generateRandomName()
println(randomName)
```

This will print a randomly generated name each time you call the function.

